  "prompt": "What does a flashing folder with question mark mean on a Macbook?",
  "response": "A **flashing folder with a question mark** on a MacBook indicates that your Mac cannot find a valid startup disk or operating system. This typically happens when the Mac is trying to boot but can't locate a bootable system on the internal drive, external drive, or any connected storage devices.\n\n### Common Causes:\n1. **Corrupted or Missing Startup Disk**: The Mac\u2019s startup disk (usually the internal drive) may be corrupted, or the operating system is missing or damaged.\n2. **Incorrect Startup Disk Selection**: The Mac may be trying to boot from an external drive or partition that doesn\u2019t contain a valid operating system.\n3. **Failing Hard Drive**: The internal hard drive or SSD may be physically damaged or failing.\n4. **Disconnected Drive**: The internal drive\u2019s cable might have become loose (common in older MacBooks).\n\n### How to Fix It:\n1. **Restart and Check Startup Disk**:\n   - Restart your Mac and hold down the **Option (\u2325) key** during startup to access the Startup Manager.\n   - Select the correct startup disk (usually named \"Macintosh HD\") if it appears.\n\n2. **Use macOS Recovery**:\n   - Restart your Mac and hold down **Command (\u2318) + R** during startup to enter macOS Recovery.\n   - In Recovery Mode, you can:\n     - **Reinstall macOS**: Reinstall the latest compatible version of macOS.\n     - **Repair Disk**: Use **Disk Utility** to check and repair your startup disk.\n     - **Restore from Backup**: Restore your Mac from a Time Machine backup.\n\n3. **Check Hardware Connections (for older MacBooks)**:\n   - If you're comfortable opening your laptop, check the internal drive\u2019s connection to the logic board (this is more common in models with mechanical hard drives).\n\n4. **Diagnose Drive Issues**:\n   - If Disk Utility in Recovery Mode shows errors or can\u2019t repair the drive, the drive may be failing and need replacement.\n\n5. **Contact Apple Support**:\n   - If none of the above works, your Mac may have a hardware issue. Contact Apple Support or visit an Apple Store for assistance.\n\nIf your Mac still won\u2019t boot after troubleshooting, it\u2019s likely a hardware or drive failure, and you may need professional help or a replacement drive.",
